<H4>    Denies Report of Deng Appearance </H4>

<F P=102> HK2306092194 Hong Kong AFP in English 0829 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK2306092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (AFP)--China emphatically denied 
Thursday a Beijing-backed Hong Kong newspaper report that 
paramount leader Deng Xiaoping had made a rare public appearance 
in the northeastern coastal city of Qingdao. 
  "This report is not true," Foreign Ministry spokesman Wu 
Jianmin told a weekly press briefing. 
  In a front-page article published Thursday, Wen Wei Po said 
Deng's trip took place recently and quoted the 89-year-old 
Chinese leader as telling local officials in Qingdao that China 
"must not have a multi-party system." 
  The official rejection of the detailed report, which quoted 
what were described as authoritative sources, was unusual given 
the fact that the Wen Wei Po is backed by Beijing and often used 
by the Chinese authorities. 
  Asked to clarify Deng's present whereabouts, Wu said simply: 
"Mr. Deng Xiaoping is wherever he is." 
  Deng's last public appearance was at Lunar New Year in 
February when he appeared on Shanghai television looking frail 
and physically supported by his daughters. 
  The ailing leader's health is a constant source of intense 
speculation. 

</TEXT>

