<H4>    Explains Abstention on Rwanda </H4>

<F P=102> OW2306085894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0851 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (XINHUA) -- A Chinese Foreign 
Ministry spokesman explained here this afternoon why China has 
abstained from voting on the UN Security Council bill 
authorizing France dispatching troops for humanitarian 
intervention in Rwanda. 
  "The action authorized by the UN Security Council resolution 
at present is not guaranteed of cooperation and consent by the 
parties to the conflict in Rwanda," the spokesman said in the 
weekly news conference. 
  "In view of this, China has abstained on the vote." 
  He said that since the Rwanda crisis occurred, China has 
constantly followed the development of the events in that 
country. 
  "At present the situation in Rwanda is continuing to 
aggravate and the humanitarian conditions in that country are 
becoming increasingly grim, and we support efforts of the 
international community to help end the crisis in Rwanda and 
remove the miserable plight of the Rwanda people as soon as 
possible. 
  "In the meantime, it is our belief that it is an 
indispensable condition for the success of UN Peace-keeping 
operation to obtain the consent of the parties concerned, and to 
obtain the cooperation of the countries and regional 
organizations concerned," he said. 

</TEXT>

