<H3> <TI>   Clinton Praises Russia's Joining NATO Partnership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Praises Russia's Joining NATO Partnership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206221894 Beijing XINHUA in English 2125 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206221894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 22 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton welcomed today what he called Russia's "far-sighted 
choice" of joining NATO's Partnership for Peace program. 
  In a ceremony celebrating the 50th anniversary of the 
signing 
of a bill aiding World War Two veterans, Clinton said the 
Russian move was "another step on our long road in man's 
everlasting quest for peace." 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev signed the documents 
in Brussels today. Moscow was 21st nation to join the program 
that covers joint planning and exercises and other consultations. 
  At the Brussels ceremony, Kozyrev and U.S. Secretary of 
State 
Warren Christopher announced that Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin will visit Washington in September. 
  Before the September trip, Yeltsin will meet Clinton in 
Naples, Italy, during the July summit of the seven 
industrialized nations. 
  In a separate development, U.S. Vice President Al Gore 
opened 
two days of talks with Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin on space, trade, energy and environment cooperation. 
  Both Gore and Chernomyrdin are leading several joint 
U.S.-Russian committees working on the related areas. 
  The committees, established 14 months ago during Clinton's 
meeting with Yeltsin in Vancouver, Canada, are having their 
third meeting here. 
  They are expected to sign a number of agreements on 
cooperation in space exploration, oil and gas production and 
environmental protection. 

</TEXT>

