<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Tries To Calm `Nervous' Financial Markets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Tries To Calm `Nervous' Financial Markets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206224594 Beijing XINHUA in English 2223 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 22 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton today tried to calm down nervous financial markets, 
saying the U.S. economy was fundamentally "very sound." 
  Speaking to reporters at the White House, Clinton minimized 
Tuesday's [21 June] plunge in the value of the dollars. 
  "Let me just emphasize that the dollar as you know is traded 
in big multinational markets with other currencies and they go 
up and down," the President said. "But the fundamental economic 
realities in this country are very sound." 
  He said the economy is growing, inflation is low and 
unemployment has dropped dramatically. "I think we just have to 
keep working on our fundamentals and in the end the markets will 
have to respond to economic realities of the American economy," 
Clinton said. 
  The U.S. dollars had plunged to a post-World War Two low 
against the Japanese yen and the lowest level in more than a 
year against the German mark Tuesday. 
  The Bank of Japan intervened today to slow the dollars's 
slide, but the German mark has retained its strength in 
international markets. 

</TEXT>

