<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Accepts ROK Proposal for Pre-Summit Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Accepts ROK Proposal for Pre-Summit Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206115594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1148 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 22 (XINHUA) -- The Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea (DPRK) notified South Korea today that it has 
accepted Seoul's proposal for a preparatory contact on June 28 
for an inter-Korean summit, much to the welcome of the latter. 
  The DPRK, in a telephone message from Premier Kang Song-san 
to his South Korean counterpart Yi Yong-tok said that a 
seven-member delegation will go to the summit preparatory talks 
at the truce village of Panmunjom. 
  "The tense political situation on the peninsula has now made 
the opening of a summit more mandatory than at any other time," 
Kang said in the message. 
  He noted, this highest-level meeting of the two sides will 
be 
a historic event which will give the 70 million Korean people 
"the joy of reconciliation and unity" and renew hopes for a 
country of peace and unification. 
  A South Korean Government official welcomed the DPRK's 
reply, 
saying that "the message came within the quickest timeframe we 
had thought of and it was in agreement with our proposal. This 
suggests that they are sincere in approaching the summit." 
  After a visit to Pyongyang last week, former U.S. President 
Jimmy Carter took a message to Seoul that the DPRK's President 
Kim Il-song wants to hold a summit with South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam without delay. 
  Seoul immediately accepted and proposed a working-level 
contact at Panmunjom on the morning of June 28. 
  Some sources said Deputy Prime Minister and the National 
Unification Board (NUB) Minister Yi Hong-ku is the likely 
Seoul-side chief delegate to the contact meeting, while 
Pyongyang may send over its Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister 
Kim Yong-nam. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

