<H3> <TI>   Minister Says Anti-Drug Campaign To Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Says Anti-Drug Campaign To Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2306022194 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1117 GMT 
22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2306022194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 22 (CNS) -- The Minister of Public 
Security, Mr. Tao Siju, said today that resolute measures would 
be continuously taken in China's anti-drug trafficking work this 
year and in the coming years to prevent drugs from flowing into 
China. 
  Speaking at a meeting held by the state anti-drug 
trafficking 
committee, Mr. Tao said despite of notable achievements made in 
the country's anti-drug trafficking campaign since last year, 
situation of drug-related crimes remained serious due to effects 
of the worldwide drug-related crimes. The anti-drug trafficking 
campaign was arduous with drug trafficking activities rampant in 
the frontier area of the southwest China and existence of 
illegal planting of opium poppies. Therefore, the campaign 
should not slack off. 
  Mr. Tao said top priority would be given to the frontier 
area 
of the southwest China such as Yunnan Province and Guangxi 
Province in terms of crackdown of border drug trafficking. 
These two provinces should intensify their anti-drug 
trafficking campaigns in order to prevent drugs made outside 
China from passing through the territory of China. 

</TEXT>

