<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangxi Sets Up Arable Land Protection Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiangxi Sets Up Arable Land Protection Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206065394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0635 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206065394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nanchang, June 22 (XINHUA) -- Arable land protection 
areas, to ensure the success of intensive farming, stable output 
and freedom from drought and waterlogging, have been set up in 
Jiangxi province. 
  The per capita arable land in this major grain-producing 
region averages 0.97 mu (one mu equals 0.065 ha) in Jiangxi. 
And the figure is decreasing along with industrialization, 
urbanization and population growth. The shortage of arable land 
is becoming an increasing obstacle to the development of 
agriculture and the economy as a whole. 
  Land in the protection areas can only be used for planting, 
and no house building, soil removal or brick making are allowed. 
Also banned are the digging of fish-raising pools or graves and 
tree planting. 
  With the setting up of arable land protection areas farmers 
no longer worry about their land being "confiscated". This 
gives them confidence to throw themselves wholeheartedly into 
farming. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

