<H3> <TI>   Lu Ping Meets Former Hong Kong Public Functionaries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lu Ping Meets Former Hong Kong Public Functionaries </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306143494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1429 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (XINHUA) -- Lu Ping, director of 
the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, 
expressed the hope here today that the civil servants in Hong 
Kong focus all their attention on their work and do not worry 
about seniority with pay. 
  The seniority with pay has been stipulated clearly in the 
basic law and there is also financial guarantee in this regard, 
Lu said, referring to the idea that a fund be set up before 
China resumes the exercise of power over Hong Kong in 1997. 
  With its promises on this and other matters, the Chinese 
government will never try to shift its responsibility, Lu told a 
visiting delegation from the association of the former senior 
civil servants of Hong Kong, led by former secretary for land 
and works Chan Nai-keong. 
  Hong Kong civil servants can continue their service after 
1997, Lu said. Only the chief civil servants will have to be 
nominated by the chief administrator of the Hong Kong Special 
Administrative Region and confirmed by the central government, 
which is designed to make the future government highly efficient. 
  During the meeting, Lu Ping also solicited opinions from the 
group on the links between the future executive and legislative 
bodies. 
  Some proposed that more Hong Kong civil servants should have 
access to Chinese courses on the mainland to enable them to 
learn more about it, with which Lu agreed. 

</TEXT>

