<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Holding Strategic Trade Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Holding Strategic Trade Talks With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306082194 Taipei CNA in English 0729 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 23 (CNA) -- Republic of China [ROC] 
trade and defense officials will discuss the control of certain 
high-tech exports with their U.S. counterparts when the two 
sides meet for strategic trade consultations in Washington on 
Tuesday [28 June] and Wednesday. 
  Since the two sides signed a memorandum of understanding on 
the protection of trade in strategic commodities -- such as 
computers that can be used for military purposes -- and 
technical data in 1990, they have held regular meetings. 
  The ROC, in the spirit of the memorandum, has mapped out 
regulations governing the export and import of high-tech 
products. One of these requirements is that domestic 
manufacturers must receive approval from the Board of Foreign 
Trade (BOFT) before importing such products. 
  A BOFT official said that the idea of controlling hi-tech 
products first came from the international Coordinating 
Committee for Multilateral Export Control, whose original aim 
was to keep high-tech products from falling into the hands of 
communist countries. With the collapse of communism, however, 
its focus has shifted to keeping such products out of the hands 
of terrorists. 
  The official said that the government is now preparing a 
list 
of high-tech products subject to export control, and it is 
expected that certain information and machinery products would 
be affected. 

</TEXT>

