<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communications Sector Using More Foreign Funds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communications Sector Using More Foreign Funds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306100894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0949 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (XINHUA) -- Since the early 1980s, 
the Ministry of Communications has used loans of about 2.5 
billion U.S. dollars from the World Bank and the Asian 
Development Bank, as well as 290 billion Japanese yen from the 
Japanese Government, to construct communications infrastructures. 
  Huang Zhendong, minister of communications, said in a press 
conference today that China has used foreign capital to 
construct a host of docks in the ports of Shanghai, Tianjin, 
Guangzhou, Qinhuangdao, Rizhao, Lianyungang and Qingdao, 
increasing the handling capacity by 43 million tons. 
  Twenty-three provinces, autonomous regions and 
municipalities 
have used or are going to use loans from international financial 
institutions or foreign governments to construct 7,000 km of 
highways. 
  Besides, direct investment in highway or port 
infrastructures 
by foreign business people has also advanced considerably, he 
said. 
  As for opening to the outside world, Huang said, by the end 
of 1993 China's water transport ports open to foreign vessels 
had grown to 107 in number, and 35 highway transport ports are 
now open to foreign vehicles from neighboring countries. 
  In addition, China has signed maritime agreements with 43 
countries and signed governmental road transport agreements with 
eight countries; 577 joint ventures in highway transportation 
and water transport businesses and vehicle services have been 
approved, of which 415 are in the road transport sector, 66 in 
automobile services, and 96 in water transportation. 
  Huang said that his ministry will take advantage of all 
favorable opportunities and provide a list of infrastructure 
projects with high economic returns to attract foreign capital, 
adhering to state industrial development policies to solve the 
problem of inadequate investment. 
  He said that there are good prospects for the communications 
sector's use of foreign funds. Guangdong province alone has 
signed letters of intent on the use of 3.5 billion U.S. dollars 
in foreign funds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

