<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Price Controls Continued on Certain Commodities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Price Controls Continued on Certain Commodities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2306023294 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 1041 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2306023294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 21 Jun (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE) -- While 
gradually removing price controls where appropriate over the 
next few years, China will continue to exercise direct state 
control over the prices of five types of commodities and 
services. 
  The five types of commodities and services are: 
  Less competitive commodities that have a great bearing on 
social stability and on the long-term development of the 
national economy, such as crude oil, natural gas, and a few rare 
metals; 
  Commodities whose prices are strictly controlled by the 
government including some medicines and weapons; 
  Living quarters offered to civil servants and low-income 
earners; 
  Utilities where competition is inappropriate, such as public 
transport, urban water and gas supplies, electricity for general 
and production purposes, rail passenger and freight transport, 
the mail service, and telecommunications; 
  Major facilities and services such as various types of 
social 
public insurance, public education, and health care. 

</TEXT>

