<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country's Labor Service Industry Abroad Thriving </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Country's Labor Service Industry Abroad Thriving </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306045094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0216 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenyang, June 23 (XINHUA) -- China has set up over 
400 firms involved in overseas labor services, and they are 
undertaking contracted projects in more than 170 countries and 
regions throughout the world. 
  The latest report from the relevant government department 
shows that a total of more than 48,000 overseas labor service 
projects have been signed since 1979 by various types of Chinese 
service companies, involving 34.16 billion U.S. dollars, with an 
accumulated turnover of 20.74 billion U.S. dollars. 
  The report also indicates that in the first four months of 
this year the overseas labor service contracts signed reached 
2.05 billion U.S. dollars with a turnover of 1.44 billion U.S. 
dollars, a hefty rise from the same period of last year. 
  In 1993 China signed over 11,600 such contracts worth 6.8 
billion U.S. dollars, with an overall turnover of 4.538 billion 
U.S. dollars, and about 174,000 experts and skilled workers were 
sent abroad. 
  Over the past few years China has contracted various 
projects 
in industry, agriculture and the service industries, including 
oil refineries and textile factories. 
  China's overseas services industry began almost at the same 
time as the reform and open policies were initiated in the late 
1970s and early 1980s. Before this, China used to render free 
labor services abroad, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

