<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Happy' About DPRK Developments </H4>

<F P=102> OW2306092194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0909 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (XINHUA) -- China is happy to see 
the positive developments on the Korean nuclear issue and 
appreciates the wise attitude adopted by the parties concerned 
for a peaceful settlement of the issue, Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman Wu Jianmin said here today. 
  U.S. President Clinton announced today that the U.S. would 
hold the third round of talks with DPRK in Geneva in early July 
to seek an overall improvement of relations between the two 
countries, Wu noted at a press conference here this afternoon. 
  He continued that according to Clinton, the U.S. would also 
stop pushing for sanctions against DPRK in the UN Security 
Council. Meanwhile, DPRK and ROK have reached an agreement on 
holding preliminary talks for a summit meeting between them. 
  Wu said, China is happy to see these positive developments 
on 
the Korean nuclear issue and appreciates the wise attitude 
adopted and positive efforts made by the parties concerned for a 
peaceful settlement of this issue. 
  The spokesman stressed that dialogue, instead of exerting 
pressure, is the basic way for a peaceful and proper settlement 
of the Korean nuclear issue. "This conforms to the interests of 
all parties and serves peace and stability on the peninsula." 
  China sincerely hopes that all parties concerned will 
treasure and seize upon this important turning point, persist in 
consultation and dialogue with an equal, pragmatic and sincere 
approach and make constructive efforts to bring about a 
denuclearized, peaceful and stable Korean peninsula, he said. 

</TEXT>

