<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Meets Former Public Functionaries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Meets Former Public Functionaries </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Transition </H4>

<F P=102> OW2306124394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1233 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 23 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today that it was 
extremely important to stabilize the ranks of Hong Kong's civil 
servants in the transitional period. 
  "This is because Hong Kong's administrative work has to rely 
on its civil servants. 
  "The smooth transfer of power and stable transition as well 
as its special administrative region's management after 1997 
will also rely on them," said Qian at a meeting with a 
delegation from the Association of the Former Senior Civil 
Servants of Hong Kong, led by former Secretary for Land and 
Works Chan Nai-keong. 
  Qian said that both Sino-British Joint Statement and the 
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region make 
clear stipulations on the continuous employment of civil 
servants. 
  The aim is to maintain the civil servants' stabilization, he 
added. 
  Qian described the delegation's visit to Beijing as of great 
significance, adding: "We support you to set up the association 
of the former senior civil servants of Hong Kong." 
  Qian said after Hong Kong's return to the motherland, civil 
servants will serve the government of its special administrative 
region and the Hong Kong residents as well. This is in 
conformity with loving the motherland and loving Hong Kong, he 
said. 
  Qian expressed the hope that the Hong Kong civil servants 
will do their best to be responsible in their work and serve the 
Hong Kong residents well in the remaining years of the 
transitional period. 
  He stressed that Hong Kong is a center of finance, economy 
and information and also an economic city, so administrative 
management plays a leading role and its high efficiency should 
be ensured. 
  Lu Ping, director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office 
of the State Council, took part in the meeting. 

</TEXT>

