------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Motorcycle               |203,400                  |172.7                    | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Industrial economic efficiency was raised. The 1993 
composite index number for industrial economic efficiency rose 
to 121.3 from 102.1 in 1992. The 1993 sales rate for industrial 
goods was 96.1 percent, up 0.6 percentage points over the 
previous year; the rate of profits and taxes to capital was 13.1 
percent, up 2.8 percentage points; and all-personnel labor 
productivity (in terms of added value) rose from 15,067 to 
22,286 yuan. However, a relatively large number of state 
enterprises operated at a loss. 
  The construction industry grew quickly. The industry's 1993 
added value was 29.5 billion yuan, up 15.1 percent on the 
previous year. Housing under construction undertaken by state 
building enterprises covered 28.3669 million square meters, up 
36 percent, but housing completed only covered 7.3411 million 
square meters, down 7.2 percent. The industry's 1993 overall 
labor productivity was 30.3 percent higher than the previous 
year, while per-capita profits and taxes increased by 36.6 
percent. 
  Geological prospecting made new progress in 1993. Two areas 
rich in important mineral resources were located, great progress 
was made in three prospecting areas, and more reserves of 
copper, antimony, gold, and kaolin were proven. Geologic 
prospecting teams, using machinery, drilled to a total depth of 
610,000 meters into core rock for mineral deposits 
<H5>  3. Fixed Assets Investment </H5>
  Investment in fixed assets grew rapidly. Fixed-assets 
investment across society in 1993 totaled 146.114 billion yuan, 
up 58.5 percent over the previous year. Fixed-assets investment 
by state-owned units was 103.355 billion yuan, up 71.3 percent; 
by collectively owned units it was 29.594 billion yuan, up 41.4 
percent; and by individual residents in urban and rural areas it 
was 13.165 billion yuan, up 20.6 percent. Of investment by 
state-owned units, 57.089 billion yuan went to infrastructure, 
up 68.6 percent; 19.629 billion yuan to transformation projects, 
up 52.7 percent; and 24.728 billion yuan to building commercial 
housing, up 96.9 percent. Construction projects in progress 
funded by state-owned units was valued at 310.842 billion yuan. 
More projects began construction. 
  The investment pattern continued to be adjusted. Of 
investment in capital construction and transformation, 1.117 
billion yuan was provided to primary industry, up 37.1 percent, 
but its share of total investment dropped to 1.5 from 1.7 
percent in the previous year; 33.837 billion yuan to secondary 
industry, up 59 percent, but its proportion dropped from 45.6 to 
44.1 percent--investment in industries providing energy and 
producing raw and semi-finished materials rose 61.1 percent over 
the previous year's figure with its proportion of total 
investment in secondary industry rising from 55.6 to 56.3 
percent; 41.764 billion yuan went to tertiary industry, up 69.6 
percent, with its share climbing from 52.7 to 54.4 
percent--investment in transport and post and telecommunications 
services increased 64.8 percent over the preceding year, with 
its share of total investment in tertiary industry down from 
56.8 to 55.2 percent. 
  Construction of key projects proceeded smoothly. A total of 
21.626 billion yuan was spent on large and medium projects, 
accounting for 95.4 percent of the relevant planned investment 
in 1993. Investment in key provincial projects amounted to 
15.799 billion yuan, basically fulfilling the 1993 plan. Most 
of the 10 wholly invested [quan tou 0356 2121] projects, 
including the Shajiao A Power Plant Phase Two, were completed as 
planned and the six individually invested [dan tou 0830 2121] 
projects, including the pumped-storage [chou shui xu neng 2132 
3022 5552 5174] Hydroelectric Power Station phase One project 
have gone into operation. 
  Principal productive capacity increased in 1993 included: 
Generating capacity by 3.88 million kw; expressways by 150 km; 
first, second, and third-grade highways by 1,707 km; 199 km of 
railroad put into service; 51 ports, wharfs, and berths; 7.98 
million tonnes of port capacity; 1.12 million telephones 
installed in urban areas; and 8 million tonnes of cement output. 
<H5>  4. Transport and Post and Telecommunications Services </H5>
  Transport and post and telecommunications services were 
expanded in an all-round way. Added value in 1993 was 15.8 
billion yuan, an increase of 20.3 percent over the previous 
year. But "bottlenecks" in transport still presented noteworthy 
restrictions on economic growth, railroads were excessively 
burdened, and the warranted supply rate of railroad cars [che pu 
bao zheng lu 6508 4122 0202 6086 3764] fell. 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Freight Volume Delivered, Handled in 1993                                    | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Total freight volume     |300.9 billion tonne/km,  |3.2                      | 
